  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Further Memorial
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant humbly submits this word.

    Your servant has heard it said that Heaven sends forth the virtuous to salvage the people of all lands. Thus does talent contain the treasures of earth, and nature harmonize with heaven's accord. High have the gates of virtue been opened, and deep has the imperial house been set right.

    Your servant reflects with reverence: The Grand Commandant, Minister of State, possesses the immortal bearing of Zhang Liang of Han, the scholarly spirit of Confucius of Lu. He pursues the hearts of the heroes of ancient dynasties and refines the essence of the five elements. Now as spring's light fully blooms, all celebrate your noble birthday. The four quarters feast upon the grace of the open gates; the myriad peoples present their earnest libations of longevity.

    Your servant humbly wishes that the martial codes be briefly unfurled to quietly dispel baleful vapors, and that the phoenix-drawn carriage swiftly return to forever kindle an age of clarity. Then may you learn the subtle arts of the immortal White Stone, and follow the blessed wanderings of the Crimson Pine Master. Upon the dragon's head, five-colored clouds gather—long has been the toil of westward gazing. The leopard-tail banner points toward the Twin Capitals as you briefly undertake the northern campaign, soon to raise high the merit of vanquishing calamity, and then to perform the rites of communion with the Realized Ones.

    Your servant, dwelling in this great hall, offers prayers for long life as spring deepens, unable to contain the fervent joy of this celebration. With this humble memorial, he respectfully submits his sincere devotion.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zhang Liang (張良), the legendary strategist of Han, was known for his immortal wisdom and otherworldly abilities.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Five Elements (五行) refer to the foundational forces of creation in Chinese cosmology: wood, fire, earth, metal, and water.'
  - key: ''
    value: White Stone and the Crimson Pine Master are Daoist immortals known for their spiritual prowess and mastery of transcendent arts.
  - key: ''
    value: The Twin Capitals likely refers to Chang'an and Luoyang, the great capitals of China's golden ages.
